a. NEG-operator: a negative phrase in a scope position;
b. Scope position: left-peripheral A′-position [Spec, XP] or [YP, XP].

N-words differ from regular indefinites in that they come with a roofing requirement (Ladusaw 1992) which must be met at the sentence level. Roofing in Ladusaw is stated as a binding requirement: n-words must be bound by a semantically appropriate operator. In Giannakidou and Quer (1995, 1997) and Giannakidou (1997) this requirement is generalized to non-veridical operators. Negation, of course, is not strictly speaking a variable binder since it is not a quantificational operator;
4
 roofing, then, is better rephrased as a requirement that existential closure apply under negation (Giannakidou 1998). So, for the sentence we just discussed in (9a), we will have the structure in (15):

(89) 








Domain:
{Frank, Bill}


Q:
{Frank arrived, Bill arrived, Nobody arrived}
